            {
                id = "whistleblower", speaker = "Scrivener Pol",
                text = "*(He goes white, then very still, the word landing like a verdict he's been avoiding.)* A whistleblower. *(quietly.)* ...That's — no. No, I'm a *copyist*, I sell *pages*, I'm not *brave*, I'm not some — *(he stops, because his own hands betray him: they're still copying, even now, even talking to you, the pen moving on its own.)* ...Gods. Look at them. My hands kept *going.* *(he sets the pen down with effort.)* You're right. The coin stopped mattering months ago — my sister's debt's been *paid* since winter, Returned. *Paid.* And I *kept copying.* I told myself it was habit, momentum, fear of stopping — but I kept copying the sealed truth after the reason ran out *because someone has to and I'm the one with the ink.* *(he laughs, terrified and amazed at himself.)* I'm a whistleblower. I've been one since winter and too scared to know it. *(he meets your eyes.)* That's worse. That's so much worse. A smuggler can *stop.* A man who copies the truth because it's *true* can't, and they hang men for that here, and I — *(steadying)* — and I'm going to keep doing it anyway. Help me do it *right*, before doing it *frightened* gets me killed for nothing.",
